$$title: Magnetic field
$$use-outline: true

Always dipoles

<m>\hat{F} = \hat{I} \times \hat{B}</m>
<m>\vec{F_b} = q ( \vec{v} \times \vec{B})</m>
	[N s / C m = T (Tesla)]
	or G (Gauss) = 10^-4 T
	
<m>\vec{F_{tot}} = q (\vec{E} + \vec{v} \times\vec{B})</m>
Electric field can do work on a charge, but a magnetic field cannot - force is always perpendicular to motion

